<p><strong>Purpose:</strong> This blog explains how to create a <strong>dynamic password history</strong> mechanism with PAM (Pluggable Authentication Modules). PAM currently allows configuring a static number of old passwords to prevent reuse, but does not natively support a dynamic model â€” especially where password changes are restricted to once per day.</p>
<li><strong>Purpose:</strong> Preserves previous shadow entries, useful for recovery or rollback if corruption occurs during password changes.</li>
</ul>


<h2>ðŸ”¹ Problem Statement</h2>
<p>How do we create a <strong>dynamic password history</strong> in PAM? By default, PAM only supports a fixed <code>remember=N</code> setting. We want a method where the <strong>number of previous passwords remembered changes dynamically</strong>, based on time elapsed since the last password modification.</p>


<h2>ðŸ”¹ Approach 1: Dynamic Password History</h2>


<h3>Steps</h3>
<ol>
<li>Use the <code>oshadow</code> file to determine the <strong>last password modification date</strong> for a given user.</li>
<li>When a password is changed:
<ul>
<li>Read the last modification date from <code>oshadow</code>.</li>
<li>Calculate the number of days between that date and the current time.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>Insert into <code>opasswd</code> a number of password history entries equal to the number of days since the last modification.</li>
<li>Adjust the number of saved password hashes in <code>opasswd</code> accordingly.</li>
<li>Each time a password changes:
<ul>
<li>Backup the current <code>opasswd</code> to <code>opasswd_old</code>.</li>
<li>Update both <code>opasswd</code> and <code>opasswd_old</code> with the new password entry.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>If the configured number of previous passwords changes (increased or decreased):
<ul>
<li>Reconstruct <code>opasswd</code> from <code>opasswd_old</code> to match the new required count.</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ol>


<div class="note">
<p><strong>Notes:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>This algorithm works across all PAM versions that use <code>opasswd</code> and <code>oshadow</code>.</li>
<li>You can also leverage the <code>chage</code> utility for managing password expiry and aging.</li>
<li><strong>Best practice:</strong> Always create a copy of <code>opasswd</code>, <code>opasswd_old</code>, and <code>oshadow</code> before making changes. Apply modifications on the copy, then rename it back to the original file for safety.</li>
</ul>
</div>


<h2>ðŸ”¹ Pros</h2>
<ul>
<li>Password history is tied to <strong>days</strong>, making it more flexible.</li>
<li>Number of previous passwords can be <strong>increased or decreased dynamically</strong>.</li>
</ul>


<h2>ðŸ”¹ Cons</h2>
<ul>
<li>Requires a <strong>fast algorithm</strong> to efficiently update <code>opasswd</code>.</li>
<li>Scalability concerns: For large numbers of users, file size grows quickly.
<br><em>Example: With 100 users, each storing 365 passwords (1 year of daily history), the <code>opasswd</code> file will contain 36,500 entries.</em>
</li>
</ul>


<h2>ðŸ”¹ Conclusion</h2>
<p>By integrating both <code>opasswd</code> and <code>oshadow</code>, you can design a <strong>dynamic password history mechanism</strong> on top of PAMâ€™s current capabilities. While this approach increases flexibility and security, it comes with challenges of performance and scalability â€” making it best suited for systems with a <strong>limited number of users</strong> or specialized compliance requirements.</p>
